{"slug": "divine", "root": "divine", "category": "divination", "gloss": "to foretell the hidden", "definition": "To divine is to discover the hidden — especially the future — by supernatural means. *Divination* is the whole art; a *diviner* practices it. The word claims a godlike power of sight.", "history": "Latin *divinare*, 'to foresee,' from *divinus*, 'of a god': to divine is to do what the gods do, know what is hidden. The Roman world formalized it into a state science — augury, haruspicy, the reading of oracles — that Cicero could both catalogue and doubt in his *De Divinatione*. Water-diviners kept the word literal into modern times; Magic names a card-drawing spell 'Divination' — foresight as card advantage.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. divine", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "Cicero, De Divinatione", "where": "Reference"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Latin divinare ‘to foresee’, from divinus ‘of a god’", "first": "c. 1374", "note": "To divine is to do what the gods do — to know the future. Same root as ‘deity’ and ‘divinity.’", "hook": "Foresight as a divine borrowing.", "lang": "Latin"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 31, "oracle_total": 10, "in_flavor_cards": 31, "in_oracle_cards": 7, "name_match_count": 29, "by_variant": {"divine": 33, "divining": 4, "divination": 3, "divined": 1}, "first_year": 1996, "colors": {"U": 8, "W": 37, "B": 7, "G": 5, "C": 6, "R": 2}, "by_year": {"1996": 1, "1998": 1, "2000": 3, "2001": 1, "2006": 1, "2007": 2, "2008": 2, "2009": 1, "2010": 2, "2011": 2, "2012": 1, "2013": 1, "2014": 3, "2015": 1, "2016": 1, "2018": 5, "2019": 2, "2020": 4, "2021": 6, "2022": 4, "2023": 3, "2024": 7, "2025": 5, "2026": 3}}, "cards": [{"id": "b08b34